@A MGTOW Monk  AOC is also at odds with the leadership in her party. Perhaps you can find common ground there.   Perhaps that is wishful thinking.  I'm just trying to bring a little humor to the situation.  The following is not addressing you Chris but is rather something that I would like to express.  Although I do not agree with trying to decertify the sovereignty of a state's election results. It is in the Constitution.  I think AOC is speaking from the heart and also using her constitutional right to freedom of expression.  Much as our president has done as well.  I gather from all the evidence available to me that this election was carried out with complete bipartisanship.  One of the most amazing things about America is this common ground.  You cannot go into a courtroom and claim such monumental fraud without good cause.  There must be a high burden of proof to take away any American's constitutional right to cast a vote. Claiming that Republicans and Democrats conspired to steal this election is a very dangerous statement by its very nature without reaching the milestones needed for such adjudication.  It is no secret that Democrats wanted to win this presidential election.  The Republicans who voted to impeach their own sitting president did so after witnessing and standing against what I assume they feel is a direct assault on liberty and justice for all.   In my humble opinion it doesn't seem honest for the president to not honor the powers and laws afforded and consequently upheld by the many states courts.  American separation of powers were created precisely to handle these exact types of situations.  I witnessed people from the left and the right doing their jobs in the election process.  This shared reality was consequently upheld in each of the state courts.   The state judiciaries allowed for the president to make his case.   Respecting the Court decisions in our election process at the state level is at the very essence of what it means to have rights as a state.  Even after this, of course it is still a congressional right to object certification at the federal level.  The supreme Court did not want or find just cause to adjudicate this matter any further.   I can only speak for myself when I say that if this election had been proven fraudulent in our judicial institutions then I would most definitely want due process and justice for the American people.  I think many people like myself believe that there are unspoken American ideals that have been desecrated by this President in continuing to claim and mislead the very people who voted for him.  If there is any evidence that shows otherwise, this President is still free to inform the American people.  The court of public opinion in America is one of our most culturally significant monuments to freedom.  If what is being said is true and that every single one of these court cases was handled unlawfully, then let that truth come out as well.  Sadly, to me I feel that so far it does not appear that many millions of Americans who support this president will ever be given the truth and a type of closure that has been a culturally present in most presidential elections in our past.   I salute all of you and hope that for the sake of this very divided country, the truth will shine through. America itself is nothing without all of us giving recognition and due respect to each other's opinions, especially in disagreement.      I have expressed my opinion as have most of you. The most American thing in the world is to recognize the right to free thought for our fellow neighbor.  Calling each other brainwashed is replacing freedom of thought with a newly adopted and seemingly highly contagious blindness to each others ideas.  This spreading wildfire of championed cultural cognitive dissonance being conducted by the left and the right is trampling the very last shred of connection we have as Americans.  This is merely my opinion but I do share it with the faith that there is still a forum in which we can share dissenting points of view and hopefully hear each other. Best wishes to all you and those you love.

A few states require the governor to appoint a replacement of the same political party as the previous incumbent.
